{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534488"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:47:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:47:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14981"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585466","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585466"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:13:09+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:13:09+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14981"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14981"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.6,0.12,0.1,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7669"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7669","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7669"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14981"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45085"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"182"},{"type":"tags","id":"350"},{"type":"tags","id":"1293"},{"type":"tags","id":"1553"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"1999"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"5621"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18748"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/59673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 72-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with severe melaena for six hours. She has atrial fibrillation and takes apixaban long term. She also has a history of hypertension and osteoarthritis, for which she takes regular amlodipine and paracetamol. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale and diaphoretic. Her vital signs are as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulse rate is 120/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood pressure 95/60 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERespiratory rate 22/min\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESpO2 95% on room air\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETemperature 36.5\u00b0C. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer abdomen is soft and non-tender. Per rectal examination confirms melaena. Investigations reveal haemoglobin 72 g/L (115-165).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate reversal agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Idarucizumab","Andexanet alfa","Tranexamic acid","Vitamin K","Protamine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a major gastrointestinal bleed while anticoagulated with apixaban, a direct factor Xa inhibitor. The presence of hypotension and significant anaemia indicates this is a severe bleed requiring urgent management including anticoagulation reversal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAndexanet alfa\u003C/strong\u003E is a recombinant modified human factor Xa protein that acts as a decoy receptor, binding and sequestering factor Xa inhibitors like apixaban and rivaroxaban. It is the specific reversal agent for these medications in the setting of life-threatening bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVitamin K\u003C/strong\u003E is used to reverse warfarin anticoagulation, typically along with prothrombin complex concentrate in major bleeding. It would not reverse the effects of apixaban.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProtamine\u003C/strong\u003E is used to reverse unfractionated heparin and low molecular weight heparin. It has no effect on direct oral anticoagulants like apixaban.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIdarucizumab\u003C/strong\u003E is a monoclonal antibody fragment specifically designed to reverse the anticoagulant effects of dabigatran, a direct thrombin inhibitor. It would not be effective for apixaban reversal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E is an antifibrinolytic agent that can be useful as an adjunct in managing bleeding but is not a specific reversal agent for any anticoagulant. While it may be used alongside appropriate reversal agents, it would not be sufficient alone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to anticoagulation reversal, management would include fluid resuscitation, blood product support, and urgent endoscopy to identify and treat the source of bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin K and prothrombin complex concentrate are used to reverse warfarin anticoagulation in major bleeding.","Idarucizumab is the specific reversal agent for dabigatran.","Andexanet alfa is used to reverse factor Xa inhibitors like apixaban and rivaroxaban."],"references":["Gorr, S.H. Yun Lu, L. Hung, E. Reversal of direct oral anticoagulants: Highlights from the Anticoagulation Forum guideline. Cleveland Clinic Journal of Medicine February 2021, 88 (2) 98-103; DOI: https://doi.org/10.3949/ccjm.88a.19133","White K, Faruqi U, Cohen AAT. New agents for DOAC reversal: a practical management review. Br J Cardiol. 2022 Jan 12;29(1):1. doi: 10.5837/bjc.2022.001. PMID: 35747314; PMCID: PMC9196076."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45085"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14981"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45085","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/45085"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-08T16:08:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-08T16:09:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7669"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"59673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc8a","name":"Pharmacology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}}